{"focus":{"id":"9f501d5a-9b19-5016-af9e-f3feea7a1f89","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c6d88-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.A.1","description":"Know precise definitions of angle, circle, perpendicular line, parallel line, and line segment, based on the undefined notions of point, line, distance along a line, and distance around a circular arc.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.A","level":"standard"},"ancestors":[{"id":"53375445-0a44-5b95-a47d-fdb93e5b2298","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f6012-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.MD.C.5","description":"Recognize angles as geometric shapes that are formed wherever two rays share a common endpoint, and understand concepts of angle measurement:","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"MD","cluster":"4.MD.C","level":"standard"}],"descendants":[{"id":"fff120ce-1225-5947-ba41-aa83e8f29989","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c675d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.1","description":"Understand radian measure of an angle as the length of the arc on the unit circle subtended by the angle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"4c6416a3-4716-5779-890f-493b76f5eb0e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9da4ac-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.A.2","description":"Represent transformations in the plane using, e.g., transparencies and geometry software; describe transformations as functions that take points in the plane as inputs and give other points as outputs. Compare transformations that preserve distance and angle to those that do not (e.g., translation versus horizontal stretch).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"6f1fd016-4465-54f6-a14f-f87c31487e78","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f119a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.A.4","description":"Develop definitions of rotations, reflections, and translations in terms of angles, circles, perpendicular lines, parallel lines, and line segments.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"2b599071-8547-5521-add4-18ee082a5d2a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d9f54-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.2","description":"Explain how the unit circle in the coordinate plane enables the extension of trigonometric functions to all real numbers, interpreted as radian measures of angles traversed counterclockwise around the unit circle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"a92e46a6-062f-571f-8176-2cae037da9d9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e6ead-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.A.3","description":"Given a rectangle, parallelogram, trapezoid, or regular polygon, describe the rotations and reflections that carry it onto itself.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"94e31f65-b9f8-5b66-a544-cb5531c798ab","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa05a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.A.5","description":"Given a geometric figure and a rotation, reflection, or translation, draw the transformed figure using, e.g., graph paper, tracing paper, or geometry software. Specify a sequence of transformations that will carry a given figure onto another.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"088892fa-d4c0-5124-bbda-72204983bd4f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f0c6f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.4","description":"(+) Use the unit circle to explain symmetry (odd and even) and periodicity of trigonometric functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"4ace16fc-ec48-547d-8fe8-17bb9011e990","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f9a9b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.5","description":"Choose trigonometric functions to model periodic phenomena with specified amplitude, frequency, and midline.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"d0979cb7-6dd3-5950-9230-4dbf862eb0ee","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba00e93-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.6","description":"(+) Understand that restricting a trigonometric function to a domain on which it is always increasing or always decreasing allows its inverse to be constructed.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"c19d1d86-6056-5558-82a1-e8bc0f04654b","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0bf6b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.C.8","description":"Prove the Pythagorean identity $\\sin^{2}(\\theta) + \\cos^{2}(\\theta) = 1$ and use it to find $\\sin(\\theta)$, $\\cos(\\theta)$, or $\\tan(\\theta)$ given $\\sin(\\theta)$, $\\cos(\\theta)$, or $\\tan(\\theta)$ and the quadrant of the angle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"5043f047-9f14-56fb-9c1f-e1d5c28af877","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0ef63-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.C.9","description":"(+) Prove the addition and subtraction formulas for sine, cosine, and tangent and use them to solve problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"80e2ab52-76b7-5dbc-a73e-49efe25ab94f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba011a4-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.B.6","description":"Use geometric descriptions of rigid motions to transform figures and to predict the effect of a given rigid motion on a given figure; given two figures, use the definition of congruence in terms of rigid motions to decide if they are congruent.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"cc2355c0-fe93-597c-ae5d-cee6e823d018","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba070dd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.B.7","description":"(+) Use inverse functions to solve trigonometric equations that arise in modeling contexts; evaluate the solutions using technology, and interpret them in terms of the context.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"64faff1c-68b2-5673-b552-23538ed39193","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa8da-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-CN.B.5","description":"(+) Represent addition, subtraction, multiplication, and conjugation of complex numbers geometrically on the complex plane; use properties of this representation for computation. *For example, $(-1 + \\sqrt{3}i)^{3} = 8$ because $(-1 + \\sqrt{3}i)$ has modulus 2 and argument $120^{\\circ}$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-CN","cluster":"HSN-CN.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"6f7e8054-4156-5c2f-b56f-b65711cfc25f","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba07418-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.B.7","description":"Use the definition of congruence in terms of rigid motions to show that two triangles are congruent if and only if corresponding pairs of sides and corresponding pairs of angles are congruent.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"1e1140f7-e845-5ee7-8b94-abfcdce11415","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0c2a8-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.B.8","description":"Explain how the criteria for triangle congruence (ASA, SAS, and SSS) follow from the definition of congruence in terms of rigid motions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"9cf05948-92aa-5ed5-8312-5d8cba784978","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0f1e1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.C.9","description":"Prove theorems about lines and angles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"b1e4c13f-eddc-544f-9fe8-7e372ba3e739","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba01ad6-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-CN.B.6","description":"(+) Calculate the distance between numbers in the complex plane as the modulus of the difference, and the midpoint of a segment as the average of the numbers at its endpoints.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-CN","cluster":"HSN-CN.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"dfbae8ab-8976-5b42-8021-5b9ab891eb6e","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9caa8d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.C.10","description":"Prove theorems about triangles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"9805c9cb-4725-5fbf-b0ba-ee33b666c18a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa609-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.B.5","description":"Use congruence and similarity criteria for triangles to solve problems and to prove relationships in geometric figures.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"d75cd0a8-4c34-5658-b919-fada1445f6cb","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9cb3ef-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-CO.C.11","description":"Prove theorems about parallelograms.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-CO","cluster":"HSG-CO.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"069ebfbe-44da-5805-b54e-1442936b729d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9da1fd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.A.2","description":"Identify and describe relationships among inscribed angles, radii, and chords.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"400c23e6-ef6b-5adf-8d27-64a4515bb8fd","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e6c76-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.A.3","description":"Construct the inscribed and circumscribed circles of a triangle, and prove properties of angles for a quadrilateral inscribed in a circle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"ec224230-3b80-5156-b6b2-82b68e282880","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f195e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.B.4","description":"Prove theorems about triangles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"19f509d0-e076-586b-9ed7-86b863cec2da","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba07a82-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.C.7","description":"Explain and use the relationship between the sine and cosine of complementary angles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"3bf30fb5-71d5-54fb-be47-574fb88880d0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fa334-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.B.5","description":"Prove the slope criteria for parallel and perpendicular lines and use them to solve geometric problems (e.g., find the equation of a line parallel or perpendicular to a given line that passes through a given point).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"1bb5899c-2929-5d5c-ad6d-44cdf5d736f2","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba014b5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-GPE.B.6","description":"Find the point on a directed line segment between two given points that partitions the segment in a given ratio.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-GPE","cluster":"HSG-GPE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"5ee2cead-ed7d-5d00-b4b1-0dd1b0fce583","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f0f18-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-C.A.4","description":"(+) Construct a tangent line from a point outside a given circle to the circle.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-C","cluster":"HSG-C.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"4b576e40-8317-5342-99a9-f84b32754936","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e6a3a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-TF.A.3","description":"(+) Use special triangles to determine geometrically the values of sine, cosine, tangent for $\\frac{\\pi}{3}$, $\\frac{\\pi}{4}$ and $\\frac{\\pi}{6}$, and use the unit circle to express the values of sine, cosine, and tangent for $\\pi-x$, $\\pi+x$, and $2\\pi-x$ in terms of their values for x, where x is any real number.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-TF","cluster":"HSF-TF.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"7d4b0f0b-04e2-50aa-a0c1-0a690ded7b09","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0c5dc-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.C.8","description":"Use trigonometric ratios and the Pythagorean Theorem to solve right triangles in applied problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"fa319b8b-ffac-571d-b9b8-067100764742","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9cacdd-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.D.10","description":"(+) Prove the Laws of Sines and Cosines and use them to solve problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"31a025e7-5652-52ad-8220-e0dcd2669f3b","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9cb64c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.D.11","description":"(+) Understand and apply the Law of Sines and the Law of Cosines to find unknown measurements in right and non-right triangles (e.g., surveying problems, resultant forces).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.D","level":"standard"}],"learningComponents":[{"id":"0af31c8a-8b82-5b02-8919-21621b5ee394","description":"Know and apply precise definitions of angles","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"},{"id":"85a750ee-d398-5ed7-b059-881ea41e7a61","description":"Know and apply precise definitions of circles","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"},{"id":"d8c95de3-bc8b-5d6f-bf4d-244b9af63aee","description":"Know and apply precise definitions of line segments","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"},{"id":"9e0d446e-8a30-58a3-b6a9-6727c7de57a1","description":"Know and apply precise definitions of parallel and perpendicular lines","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"},{"id":"dc6cd2b8-5246-551a-8c58-a4a60ca875b1","description":"Know and apply the differences between the properties of parallel and perpendicular lines","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"},{"id":"0b2fd3cb-176e-50eb-9cdb-e16c456b51a6","description":"Understand and use definitions of angles, circles, perpendicular lines, parallel lines, and line segments based on the undefined term of a point, a line, the distance along a line, and the length of an arc","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"}],"edges":[{"id":"28c09c9f-cacc-54b2-8653-a869714c3cfe","label":"buildsTowards","source":"53375445-0a44-5b95-a47d-fdb93e5b2298","target":"9f501d5a-9b19-5016-af9e-f3feea7a1f89"},{"id":"7b2bafd8-86da-5121-97fd-957de68c56d0","label":"buildsTowards","source":"64faff1c-68b2-5673-b552-23538ed39193","target":"b1e